title: Ruby Lake National Wildlife Refuge : Ruby Valley Nevada : 1994 Annual water management report 1995 Annual water management plan
name: ruby-lake-national-wildlife-refuge-ruby-valley-nevada-1994-annual-water-management-report-
notes: The water availability forecast for 1995 may be encouraging for this year, but is again discouraging for the long term recovery of refuge wetlands to objective elevations. Refuge wetlands will continue to be negatively impacted because of the present low water elevations, lack of stored ground water, and current below average snow pack water content. The 1994-95 winter snow pack water content, for the period from 1 January to 1 April, is below average at 86.7 percent, according to SCS surveys. The actual quantity of water provided by the snow pack may be underestimated because much of the snow melted during February and the first half of March due to above average temperatures. It is expected that there will be an adequate amount of water to maintain the small marsh units at or near desired management elevations. It is also expected that there will not be sufficient water available to achieve or maintain desired water management elevations in the North, East, and South Sumps during 1995. At present, the water elevation in the South Sump at the Main Boat Landing (5963.54 ft.) is 9.1 in higher than in 1994 (5962. 78 ft.) at this same time. Considering that much of the snow pack remains on the mountains because of below average ambient air temperatures and that the present elevation of the South Sump is higher than in 1994, it is highly likely that the maximum elevation of the South Sump in 1995 will exceed the maximum elevation in 1994.
